title: For Sale:  Barrett M107A1 20" CQ 50 BMG Guncrafter 50GI
postcontent:
The Barrett M107A1 .50 BMG semi-automatic rifle is an exceptional firearm! Here are some of the new upgrades:

* It has the upgraded muzzle brake which gives you less recoil, and enables you to stay on target for faster, more accurate follow up shots. The new 4 chamber muzzlebrake is also able to receive their quick attach suppressor if you ever wanted to silence your 50. (Barrett has said that currently the new muzzlebrake is not available as a separate accessory for the M82A1).

* It's made of a much stronger, lighter titanium, so even though it's very light it's more durable, and the titanium w/ the upgraded brake keeps recoil down. Also aluminum and steel areas where possible have been thinned for further weight savings without sacrificing the integrity of the design.

* The mags are much better with a tougher finish, and the mag has sight holes so you can tell exactly how many rounds you have left; our customers that hunt w/ their .50's love that feature, and our troops demand it.

* The finish on the M107's is much more durable, scratch resistant and rust resistant.

* It has the thermal cheek guard that allows the shooter to rest their face on the cheek plate and not directly on metal. Also, it's elevated which is ideal because the M107A1 has a really long, elevated mono-rail.

* It has a lightweight, quick detach bipod with modular feet.

title: For Sale:  Barrett M107A1 20" CQ 50 BMG Guncrafter 50GI
postcontent:
the Barrett M107A1 .50 BMG semi-automatic rifle is an exceptional firearm! Here are some of the new upgrades:

* It has the upgraded muzzle brake which gives you less recoil, and enables you to stay on target for faster, more accurate follow up shots. The new 4 chamber muzzlebrake is also able to receive their quick attach suppressor if you ever wanted to silence your 50. (Barrett has said that currently the new muzzlebrake is not available as a separate accessory for the M82A1).

* It's made of a much stronger, lighter titanium, so even though it's very light it's more durable, and the titanium w/ the upgraded brake keeps recoil down. Also aluminum and steel areas where possible have been thinned for further weight savings without sacrificing the integrity of the design.

* The mags are much better with a tougher finish, and the mag has sight holes so you can tell exactly how many rounds you have left; our customers that hunt w/ their .50's love that feature, and our troops demand it.

* The finish on the M107's is much more durable, scratch resistant and rust resistant.

* It has the thermal cheek guard that allows the shooter to rest their face on the cheek plate and not directly on metal. Also, it's elevated which is ideal because the M107A1 has a really long, elevated mono-rail

title: For Sale:  CUSTOM TUNED NIB Ruger New Vaquero .45 Colt - 4 5/8" Barrel
postcontent:
Looking for a good home!

What we have here, ladies and gentlemen, is a customized and tuned (and I don't throw that term around loosely. If you ask me, the words "custom" and "tactical" are thrown around way too loosely nowadays.) stainless Ruger New Vaquero in .45 Colt. 

SO, for the sake of explanation, let me tell ya why I picked customized to describe this beauty-

 1. All springs have been replaced with low-power Wolff springs, The trigger pull is now 1lb or less and the force required to rotate the cylinder is better than butter (I'm confident that you'll love it as much as I did, I'm willing to meet up with anyone with no prior commitment to buy just so you can test the action and trigger pull for yourself.) I know that main spring has been reduced to 30 lb, and if you're interested I can come up with the 'lb' reduction for the rest of the springs should you be interested ahead of time!

Also, every friction point on every part has been painstakingly honed on a super light Arkansas stone to a mirror finish without removing any metal.

2. The trigger has been aligned with trigger shims from TriggerShims.com, a website run by this great guy who sells different widths of trigger shim, reducing ALL play in the Vaquero trigger, as well as smoothing it out more. 

3. The oxblood grips (That I don't have on the vaquero in each of these pictures, as I was deciding what would work best for this particular piece) these are the grips that are on there right now, ordered brand new a few weeks ago:  http://www.ebay.com/itm/RUGER-OXBLOOD-GRIPS-NEW-VAQUERO-MONTADO-50TH-ANNIVERSARY-w-CHECKERING-/REDACTED92?pt=LH_DefaultDomain_0&hash=item3f2fd0c2f0

And, finally, I'm the original owner of this New Vaquero, and I've never fired round-one out of it. So, it's never been fired and new in box. Very high quality revolver with high quality work! A lot of blood, sweat and tears went into this one, and if you've enjoyed my projects in the past then please have a look here!

title: For Sale:  Tactical Mossberg Pistol Grip Pump 12 Gauge
postcontent: The Mossberg model 500 has never been as prestigious as the arch-competitor Remington 870, but it’s just as tried, and just as true. Here is a very attractive specimen from Mossberg’s model 500 Military & Police series. This listing is for the exact shotgun in the photos, but dealers are welcome to take any number of the same model, very similar condition, that we have on hand. Manufacturer, of course, is O.F. Mossberg & Sons of New Haven, CT. Model is 500, Persuader series; factory sku is 50411 or thereabouts. Type is pump or slide action shotgun. Construction is steel barrel and working parts all built into an alloy receiver that undercuts the 870 on weight, with durable synthetic stock and traditional synthetic forend. Finish is blued steel with semi gloss black anodized receiver. Trigger group housing is high impact black polymer, with .292 smooth faced combat trigger. Safety is top tang type. Barrel is 3 inch chambered 18 1/2 inch matte blue steel plain bead sight, with .730 vicinity Cylinder Bore muzzle. Magazine capacity is 5 rounds of 2 3/4 inch shells, or 4 rounds of 3 inch shells, 5+1 capacity on 2 3/4 inch shells. Weight empty is 6 3/4 pounds, with center of gravity at the breech. Buttstock measures 13 7/8 inches from the trigger face to the end of the 7/8 inch black rubber factory recoil pad. Stock drop is 1 1/2 inches at the comb, and 2 1/2 inches at the butt, with a right hand cant of about 3/4 inch. If this shotgun didn’t have a heat shield, we have added a trench type black polymer heat shield for the barrel, that will be obvious from the photos. This model 500 comes to us from Mossberg’s distribution system. It is what we call a factory demo, probably a sales rep’s sample or a showgirl at a Firearms Industry trade show. Surface detractions are negligible to minimal on this shotgun, as its photos show. We rate it as Excellent, perhaps Near Mint, but photos ought to suffice for our distinguished shoppers to judge finish grade for themselves. Often a person can spot the letter U stamped on the left side of the receiver above the serial number. Bore, chamber, and mechanism are all bright and clean.This 500 Special Purpose comes in a relabeled Mossberg Factory Box with factory lock, instruction manual, NSSF and NRA flyers.. Replacement pricing on mossberg com was well over $400 on this shotgun.

title: For Sale:  Ruger 50th Anniversary .44 Magnum "Flattop" New Model Blackhawk®
postcontent:
No trades 
Cash only 
Private Seller and Sale
NO Background Required 
Need to be 21 Years of Age With Nevada Id
Sturm, Ruger & Company, Inc. (NYSE: RGR) is proud to announce the return of what many shooters and collectors feel is the most handsome of all the Ruger single-action revolvers, the .44 Magnum "flattop." Originally introduced in 1956 when the powerful .44 Magnum cartridge was brand new, the Ruger .44 Magnum Blackhawk set new performance standards for the burgeoning sport of handgun hunting. With its massive chrome-molybdenum steel "flattop" frame and fluted cylinder, precision adjustable sights, and all coil-spring construction, it was a pure hunting handgun, combining power, precision, and elegance in a most pleasing form. 

Many other .44 Magnum revolvers followed the original "old model"* Ruger Blackhawk. The Ruger Super Blackhawk (1959), New Model Super Blackhawk (1973), Redhawk® (1979), Super Redhawk (1987), Bisley (1989), Vaquero® (1993), and Hunter (1996) continued to revolutionize the world of handgun shooters. Yet, many longed for the compact simplicity of Sturm, Ruger's original .44 "flattop," which was discontinued in 1962. 

Following the success of the Ruger .357 50th Anniversary New Model Blackhawk in 2005, Sturm, Ruger is proud to commemorate the 50th Anniversary of its original .44 Magnum Blackhawk. The Ruger 50th Anniversary .44 Magnum New Model Blackhawk features the trim "flattop"-style cylinder frame with "micro"-style click adjustable rear sight, a fluted cylinder, and smaller, "XR-3"-style grip frame and checkered black panels with the original black Ruger grip medallions of the very first Ruger .44 Blackhawks. A 6 1/2" blued steel barrel with a ramp front sight also gives this revolver the look of the original, while its patented Ruger New Model Blackhawk transfer bar and loading gate mechanisms give an unprecedented measure of security and convenience. The Ruger 50th Anniversary .44 Magnum New Model Blackhawk also has a gold color-filled barrel rollmark "50 YEARS OF .44 MAGNUM - 1956 TO 2006" to commemorate the introduction of the original .44 Magnum Blackhawk. New features include a patented reverse indexing pawl for easier loading and unloading and, to meet various state sales requirements, an unobtrusive internal lock under the right grip panel. 

The Ruger 50th Anniversary .44 Magnum New Model Blackhawk comes in a special red case with a unique handsome lens label. A California-approved external locking device, comprehensive instruction manual, and a special commemorative booklet detailing the history of the .44 Magnum Blackhawk complete the package. This special 50th Anniversary .44 Magnum New Model Ruger Blackhawk will only be produced in limited quantities until the end of 2006.

All the older Gen 2's had a plastic shroud over the slide release lever. It was one more thing to hang up on clothing, so they eliminated it in favor of a flat metal release, which is sleeker and easier to draw from a holster or waistband.

Includes all original paperwork and box, 2 mags, interchangeable base plates, trigger lock and key.

Includes an Armalaser TR10 laser. This is the ONLY laser made specifically to fit the Sccy. It looks factory.

Includes a black Cordura holster that fits the gun with the laser.

Very nice package for concealed carry or bedstand duty.
Full 9mm in a compact package, stainless slide and barrel for long life and no wearing out of the finish.

Cash only, no trades, face to face only.

title: For Sale:  Round Balls .457 Musket Balls
location: South St Louis County, St. Louis, Missouri
postcontent: I use soft lead and refine my lead in a Lee Production Pot. The lead pours out of the bottom spout of pot so it is clean going into mold. I use a Lee double cavity mold. I try to make them as perfect as possible. Since they are cast you can see the end where the lead is cut off at pour hole and sometimes you can see the seam from the 2 halves of molds, but this is normal. I look at each ball and give you the customer the best ones. The real bad ones I remelt. The ones with little imperfections I keep for myself to shoot out of my Ruger Old Army muzzle loading revolver. If you shoot one of those revolvers it resizes the ball when you push it into the cylinder. The Ruger Old Army takes .457 balls even though they call it 44 caliber. You can also use these balls in a slingshot or a ball mill when you make black powder. George Washington would be happy to have this quality of a musket ball for his soldiers. I sell them for $10 per 100. You can buy more than that. I believe I can put up to 500 in a small rate shipping box.                                                                                   Shipping is only $5.80. Of course we can meet in person if we are close enough. This is something I do in my spare time. I'm not getting wealthy selling these and are very time consuming to make. Lifetime NRA member. John REDACTED

title: For Trade:  Sig Sauer P220 Carry with Extras
postcontent:
I would like to trade my Sig P220 Carry SA/DA 45 ACP.  The P220 has about 1000 rounds through it (EDIT:  I just went back and looked through records, it should be much closer to 600-700), which means it is just breaking in.  I have another Sig P220 that has over 8k rounds through it, and it is just getting more and more accurate.

The P220 has factory night sights, still decently bright at night.  The barrel has some wear on the outside finish, but this is common with Sigs.  There are some very minor blems on the outer finish, and most have been touched up, and you can barely tell where they were.  It does have an accessory rail, and 2 magazines.

I have a brand new set of Warren Competition sights, plain rear, orange or green fiber optic front sight, and a Sig Short Reset Trigger kit, directly from Sig.  Neither of these have actually been installed, and still in their packages.

Let me know if you have any questions.
